<div id="review_4241555771" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4241555771" />
    <a title="Diane Yannick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1253673-diane-yannick"><img alt="Diane Yannick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468376907p2/1253673.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4241555771?book_show_action=true">Sep 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diane Yannick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diane Yannick" href="/user/show/1253673-diane-yannick">Diane Yannick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4241555771" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17891889729055648976">Please don’t skip by this book as another Catholic Church scandal book—specifically 2002 in Boston. It is much more than that as it digs deep into the meaning of faith and asks important questions. How much support will you get from family members who are quick to believe the worst about you—even though you’ve shown them who you are for a lifetime? How careful do we have to be about taking extra steps to help others in need? Do we always need to guard against the perception of wrongdoing? Is it </span>
  <span id="freeText17891889729055648976" style="display:none">Please don’t skip by this book as another Catholic Church scandal book—specifically 2002 in Boston. It is much more than that as it digs deep into the meaning of faith and asks important questions. How much support will you get from family members who are quick to believe the worst about you—even though you’ve shown them who you are for a lifetime? How careful do we have to be about taking extra steps to help others in need? Do we always need to guard against the perception of wrongdoing? Is it reasonable to expect priests to be celibate and even judged for impure thoughts? Is this the kind of God we have to answer to? As a kid I can remember going to confession and being so worried that I didn’t confess all of my sins and gave an inaccurate number for some. I was a young kid for God’s sake! <br /><br />But most thought-provoking to me about this book was this barely mentioned concept of collective guilt. Father Art wondered if he should defend himself or accept that he was part of this huge body of Catholic guilt. Some pedophiles never had to answer for their sins so is it only fair that some innocent ones shoulder some of that sin? <br /><br />The characters were carefully drawn. The slant was unique. Cliches were brought to light—do the abused become abusers? Spouting psychology does not take the place of careful analysis of each situation. Very good book.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17891889729055648976" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


