    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_153493033" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/153493033" />
    <a title="jo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/210397-jo"><img alt="jo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1237421111p2/210397.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/153493033?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="jo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="jo" href="/user/show/210397-jo">jo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/210397-jo?shelf=audio">audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/210397-jo?shelf=trauma">trauma</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/210397-jo?shelf=the-priestly-condition">the-priestly-condition</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer153493033" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9421472259215605061">at first, justifiably i think, i thought this was a story about the endless, horrible, unspeakable barrage of child molestation by bostonian priests that came to light some 15 years ago. i am a catholic but i held on to my faith in god and the church because i am quite aware of the various plagues that afflict the skin, the organs, the bone, and the blood of the church. jesus chose as his first pope, his very first peter, a man who <i>was told</i> he would betray him <i>the following day</i> and said, &quot;never!</span>
  <span id="freeText9421472259215605061" style="display:none">at first, justifiably i think, i thought this was a story about the endless, horrible, unspeakable barrage of child molestation by bostonian priests that came to light some 15 years ago. i am a catholic but i held on to my faith in god and the church because i am quite aware of the various plagues that afflict the skin, the organs, the bone, and the blood of the church. jesus chose as his first pope, his very first peter, a man who <i>was told</i> he would betray him <i>the following day</i> and said, "never!" then went on and did just that. it didn't even take a full day for the first pope to deny his god. and of course he wasn't alone, was he, because judas had done selfsame earlier that same day (this is the cream of the crop that jesus chose to be his church, so you see there's already a 16% massive failure rate there, and <b>the thing hadn't even started</b>). but the difference between judas and peter, both betrayers, neither better than the other, is that judas is so shattered by his own failure, so utterly shattered, that he goes and hangs himself (who doesn't understand him? who dare judge him?). peter, on the other hand, takes a long hard look at himself, cries bitter, bitter tears, dusts himself off, and carries on. (this attitude of peter's, btw, plays a really central role in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/575.Robert_Harris" title="Robert Harris" rel="nofollow noopener">Robert Harris</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29397486.Conclave" title="Conclave by Robert Harris" rel="nofollow noopener">Conclave</a>). no one is asking of priests bishops cardinals popes nuns regular christians that they not fail. failing massively is ALREADY IN THE CARDS. if you can, though, if you just can, pick yourself up and keep going. you are needed. <br /><br />this is a digression but self-hatred and forgiveness are, i think, a big part of this book. <br /><br />so, when i realized the book was not really, not laser-focusedly, about a priest and a boy but about a boston family, three generations of it, and a lot of bostoniana -- and when the narrator kept changing and the audio version made it all difficult to follow (there are three POV, which at the end turns out to be quite awesome) -- well i thought, hmmm. but then i talked to my girlfriend and she said all the right things, and read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/157662040?book_show_action=false" rel="nofollow noopener">switterbug's review</a>, which also says all the right things, so i kept going. <br /><br />and i'm so happy i did. cuz the priestly abuse of a little boy is perpetrated <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[not by arthur, the priest who is suspended by the cardinal and relegated to intense loneliness inside a bare apartment while things get sorted out, but by art's uncle, a priest who molested little art for years until art's newly acquired stepdad, a man who was never particularly kind to art but, it turns out, did the thing no one else had the courage to do, told the old man off and the abuse stopped. this emerges very slowly and this slow disclosure makes of this book a bit of a literary feat. what happened is that art's mom found herself single, dirt poor, and with a young child, and this generous uncle came around once a week bearing groceries, and that was the one day that everybody ate. do you sell your child so that everyone can eat at least once a week? yes you do. or you don't, but remember at least the enormous power of the priesthood in entrenched catholic communities, and the impossibility of saying no, and the blind, numb acquiescence to which mothers are pushed over and over and over. don't put the blame on the mother, is what i'm saying.<br /><br />so art grows up to be a massively traumatized man, so traumatized in fact that he literally cannot name his trauma. was he abused? was he molested? did anything really happen? and if it did, how long did it go on? weeks? months? years? maybe only a couple of days?<br /><br />we never learn whether art feels great faith or a true vocation but my suspicion is that he doesn't. we know that he keeps his head down and keeps at his job, tortured by loneliness -- a sad, unhappy, compulsively smoking man -- day in and day out. <br /><br />and then kath appears, with an 8 year old son, and they are both as lost and abandoned as art and his mother were. they are, respectively, the daughter and grandson of art's housekeeper, fran. kath is a drug addict, a broken soul. <br /><br />the thing with art, the thing we learn at the end, is that he has been tortured his entire life by what should probably be described as asexuality. he doesn't feel attracted to women. he doesn't have a sexual response to women or anything else. and he feels very much not a man. but also, well, isn't this ideal if you are a priest? the answer is, it is and it isn't. cuz how do you fight temptation if you don't have it? what virtue is there in that? and of course, all along, you are not a man. you carry this unmanliness around like a stone, like a ball and chain, like the most shameless thing ever (and it must be said that this very feminist book does a really good job of presenting the immense burden of compulsory masculinity). <br /><br />when kath comes around, however, art's sexuality wakes up. he starts off helping her, just like uncle fergus helped him and his mom, except a ton more nicely. he gets kath a place and a job and he babysits aidan with great dedication (these are difficult times for a priest to be around a kid so much, but art is helping and all he cares about is kath). and now aidan has a father and a friend, and kath does too. <br /><br />one day though art crosses the line and sleeps with kath, partly because he's come to love her, partly because he's blown away by this new, amazing sexuality that is building up in him. and kath, you know, kath has slept with so many men so much less kind.<br /><br />i want to say here that the real heartbreaker of this novel is not art but kath. art helps her and loves her and she believes him, she truly does. but after they sleep together, after <i>she accepts to do what he wants</i>, he disappears from her life entirely, because after all he's a priest, and a man who hates his sexuality. you see what jennifer haigh is doing here don't you? some people just can't win -- women and children. later, shockingly, art's brother will do exactly the same to kath, under the pretense of finding out whether art really abused aidan. it's amazing that haigh makes it work but she does. trauma visits families in open and in stealthy ways, and its damage carries on for generations upon generations. and then of course there are women and children, used for sex then thrown away by men who suddenly realize they need to be good people and go back to their families or their parishes. who, unlike peter, do not carry on, but let others pick up the mess -- if there are others at all. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />what a sad, heartbreaking, powerful, and deep story. go get yourself the book and read it. then remember that if you fuck someone over, you really, really ought to see them through. if you can. don't bail on them cuz that kinda sucks.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9421472259215605061" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


