<div id="review_272189050" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/272189050" />
    <a title="Megan O&#39;Neill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6948563-megan-o-neill"><img alt="Megan O&#39;Neill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493210115p2/6948563.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/272189050?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Megan O&#39;Neill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Megan O&#39;Neill" href="/user/show/6948563-megan-o-neill">Megan O&#39;Neill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6948563-megan-o-neill?shelf=contemporary-fiction">contemporary-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer272189050" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9552673268330906341">As someone whose entire academic career was spent in Catholic institutions, from the first day of Kindergarten at a parochial school to the moment I graduated from Duquesne University, and someone who has often cultivated good relationships with the priests at both my home parish and at school, Jennifer Haigh&apos;s beautifully-crafted novel was both touching and unsettling. While I have never, ever been in the company of a priest whose intentions were suspect, instead lucky enough to have built frie</span>
  <span id="freeText9552673268330906341" style="display:none">As someone whose entire academic career was spent in Catholic institutions, from the first day of Kindergarten at a parochial school to the moment I graduated from Duquesne University, and someone who has often cultivated good relationships with the priests at both my home parish and at school, Jennifer Haigh's beautifully-crafted novel was both touching and unsettling. While I have never, ever been in the company of a priest whose intentions were suspect, instead lucky enough to have built friendships with priests who are truly men of God, I am not someone who believes that there aren't some priests out there who falter, and worse, actively seek to abuse the trust their congregants put in them. <br /><br />But the tragic beauty of Haigh's work is that Father Arthur Breen is a victim himself, of a world who sees only those priests when they look at any collar, while the reader sees instead the man who loves so fiercely and deeply - so truly, and so innocently - that it becomes his downfall. Narrated by Father Breen's sister, the novel is a bit reminiscent of John Patrick Shanley's <i>Doubt</i>, while being something completely fresh, original, and all its own. With unexpected twists, and a topic that is handled carefully and with compassion, while also being handled realistically and honestly, it's a must-read. It really is.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9552673268330906341" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


